# .omnijs Files Are OmniAutomation Plug-ins (JavaScript)

Files with the `.omnijs` extension are OmniAutomation plug-in scripts. Always treat them as JavaScript and apply OmniAutomation-specific conventions below.

## Always Consult the Docs

OmniAutomation has its own API, syntax, and global objects. Before writing or editing code, refer to the official reference:
- Full API: https://omni-automation.com
- OmniFocus-specific: https://omni-automation.com/omnifocus/
- `URL.FetchRequest`: https://omni-automation.com/url/fetch-request.html
- `Credentials`: https://omni-automation.com/shared/credentials.html
- `Form` / `Form.Field`: https://omni-automation.com/shared/form.html
- `PlugIn` / libraries: https://omni-automation.com/shared/plugin.html

## Plug-in File Structure

Every plug-in starts with a JSON descriptor in a block comment, followed by an IIFE that returns an `action`:

```js
/*{
    "type": "action",
    "targets": ["omnifocus"],
    "identifier": "com.example.my-plugin",
    "version": "1.0",
    "label": "My Action"
}*/
(() => {
    const action = new PlugIn.Action(function(selection, sender) { ... });
    action.validate = function(selection, sender) { return true; };
    return action;
})();
```

## Key Global APIs (do NOT polyfill or import — they are injected by the runtime)

| API | Purpose |
|-----|---------|
| `PlugIn.Action` | Define the action handler |
| `PlugIn.find(id)` / `.library(name)` | Load a shared library plug-in |
| `URL.FetchRequest.fromString(url)` | Create an HTTP request (NOT `fetch`) |
| `request.fetch()` | Execute the request (returns a Promise) |
| `response.statusCode` / `response.bodyString` | Parse the response |
| `Credentials` | Securely store/retrieve tokens (keychain-backed) |
| `credentials.write(service, user, password)` | Store a credential |
| `credentials.read(service)` | Returns `{user, password}` or `null` |
| `credentials.remove(service)` | Delete stored credential |
| `Form` / `Form.Field.Password` / `Form.Field.String` | Build input dialogs |
| `Alert` | Show alerts and confirmations |
| `app.platformName` | `"macOS"` or `"iOS"` |
| `app.controlKeyDown` / `app.optionKeyDown` | Modifier key state |
| `TextAutocapitalizationType` | Autocap control for iOS form fields |

## Network Requests

Use `URL.FetchRequest` — never `fetch`, `XMLHttpRequest`, or `axios`:

```js
const request = URL.FetchRequest.fromString("https://example.com/api")
request.method = "GET"
request.cache = "no-cache"
request.headers = { "Authorization": "Bearer " + token }
const response = await request.fetch()
// response.statusCode, response.bodyString
```

## Credential Handling

Auth tokens must be stored via `Credentials`, never hardcoded:

```js
const credentials = new Credentials()
credentials.write("my-service", "username", token)
const cred = credentials.read("my-service") // { user, password }
```

## Security Notes

- Tokens and secrets must always go through `Credentials` (keychain-backed)
- `URL.FetchRequest` calls send data over the network — review headers carefully
- `console.log(response.bodyString)` may log sensitive data; avoid in production
